************************
Pre-Conference Workshops 
************************

The  Technology  for  Information Security Conference  '94  is  pleased
to announce  the following pre-Conference Workshops.   These workshops
will further your knowledge in the administration and use of security
tools  and devices.  These full-day Workshops are presented
concurrently, starting  at 9:00 a.m., December 5, 1994.
____________________________________________________________

Firewalls
A  firewall is a security mechanism that allows limited access to your
site allowing approved traffic in and out according  to  a well
thoughtout plan.   This  lets  you  select  the  services appropriate
to your needs, 
while barring others which  may  have significant  security  holes.  The
intended  audience  for  this tutorial includes network  managers,
systems  administrators, information systems managers, and others who
are considering  the implementation   of  a  security firewall or are
currently maintaining an existing firewall system.
____________________________________________________________

UNIX W/S Security
This  workshop  is  designed  to help  attendees understand  and
effectively  deal with UNIX security problems.  A common  problem is
the  difficulty  in enabling,  monitoring,  and  controlling security in
most UNIX systems.  The morning session will focus on the general
purpose UNIX workstation that is usually not afforded the same
protection as dedicated or special purpose systems.  The afternoon
session will address the nature of the network threat complicated  by
TCP/IP network services.   Systems and  network administrators,  and
security practitioners  are  encouraged  to attend this workshop.
____________________________________________________________

Client/Server Security
This workshop will address problems associated with client/server,
distributed control  issues,  the problems with authority of a
distributed application and the multiple layers of security, distributed
data issues, and denial of service  issues. Strategic planners, network
administrators,  and systems and line management should  attend this
informative session  designed to balance  the capabilities of
client/server with the problems and concerns.
____________________________________________________________

(ISC)2 Certification
Once again we will offer a workshop addressing certification  for the
information security professional. Industry has been looking for a means
of determining a security professional's qualifications and abilities
for many years.  The International Information  Systems Security
Certification  Consortium, Inc. (ISC)2 has scheduled the first exam to
be offered in April  of 1995.  Security  practitioners will  be taught
how to begin preparing themselves technically for the examination.
Candidates who sit  for the exam and maintain their certification, are
set apart as true professionals in our young industry.  This course is
critical for  he security professional and management interested in
certification of their 
information securitypractitioners.

***********************************************
Technology for Information Security '94 Conference Tracks
***********************************************

The Technology for Information Security Conference '94 is pleased to
announce the following Conference presentation Tracks. These
presentations will  provide you with a starting point for securing your
networks  from intrusion from the Internet, while providing possible
solutions  to  the prominent security issues of today.
____________________________________________________________

Federal Management
A  special track has been added to this year's conference that focuses
on issues specifically of interest andbenefit to federal managers.  The
growing  complexity of computer technology and the push for open systems
poses   a  unique management  challenge.  The Management Track provides
practical  advice and information to help managers better handle today's
security challenges.   What are today's  security challenges?  In one
session,  a  representative from the NASA Incident Response  
Center will describe the security challenges posed by threats to NASA
systems. Another presentation will provide an overview of the  major
laws  regarding  the security of federal systems, including the
implications of certifying federal  systems.   One aspect of the
certification of federal systems is that  the manager, by signing,
certifies that the system complies 
with all federal  laws.  Yet how many managers can even list or locate a
reference containing  the names of the applicable laws, much less
certify that the system  complies  with them?  Another  track  session
provides a  NASA Headquarters'  perspective on middle management
security training  that emphasizes middle management concerns about
security that differ from those of  users and executive management.
Attend these Management Track sessions for  information to better manage
the security challenges of today's complex, open systems.
____________________________________________________________

Firewalls
With the Internet becoming increasingly hostile and as more
organizations are connecting to the Internet, firewalls are the hottest
discussion topic on  the security of computer connectivity. A firewall
is a specially configured  system  that filters traffic between
networks, such as the interface between  the Internet and a LAN.  A
firewall limits traffic to help ensure a controlled  and  secure
environment, safe from outside influences.  One of the track sessions
will present  an  introduction  to firewall technology fundamentals,
including  the  basic concepts and components of firewalls, as well as
firewall variations such  as  Bastion hosts, gateways, air gaps, and
others.  Other presentations will describe firewall tools for intruder 
management and the  necessary expertise to administer firewall systems.
Managers, security professionals, and technicians should attend these
track sessions to learn  how  to apply firewall technology to promote a
safer 
work environment, even with  today's security exposures from the
Internet.
____________________________________________________________

Responses to System Penetration
We've all heard the stories of hackers penetrating sensitive networks.
This  year's conference addresses alternative actions that may result in
a greater   recovery of information and a better chance  to prevent
reoccurrence, such as the establishment of a "fishbowl" in which to
observe and track  a hacker.  Several presentations describe actual
penetrations, how they were  detected, and what was done to recover the
system.   Other presentations will describe legal remedies under
computer crime law today and prodict what we might expect in the near
future.  This track provides timely  insights and practical information
for managers and technicians as computer crime continues to proliferate.
____________________________________________________

Security for the Practitioner
An  organization uses risk management to determine how best  to  spend
its security budget.  By using a risk management approach, you can
outlay  the minimum dollars to provide a sufficient  level of security
for your 
computerized  systems.  An important factor in risk management  is
having accurate data available to make good decisions. This session will
stress the  importance of certifying threat data, how to find the  data,
how 
to process it, and how to determine its fitness for use.

Sometimes the best things in life are free!  On the Internet,  there are
many  useful  security tools and resources.  Often they can provide
needed capabilities in advance of commercial offerings. We urge
security 
professionals to come join us on a tour of the security watering holes
on the information highway.

The auditing role is evolving to keep pace with the dynamic, technology
dependent environment.   In order to contribute to an organization's
success,  auditors and security  professionals should focus on system
efficiencies  and effectiveness, stay abreast of technology  and develop
technical skills accordingly, and understand the business,  including
the relationship of control weaknesses to overall company goals.  The
audit 
session is a must for auditor and security professionals to ensure that
their  audit activities are more service oriented" and add value to the
organization.

The State of Texas has also responded to pressures of the transformation
to an information society by releasing the Texas Information Security
Standard and  Associated Guidance.  These standards affect all state
agencies and associated businesses and will be discussed during one of
the track sessions.

The Clinton Administration's National Information Infrastructure
initiative has accelerated the change to an information  society.  The
information security profession is unprepared to handle the societal
level change that this  represents. The Security for the Practitioner
Track will demonstrate how  security  policies, principles, and
practices will  help  smooth the turbulent  waters of today's
information society.  Some highlighted topics of the track  include
GSSP, Texas Information Security Standards, risk management, Internet
tools, and auditing.

The development of Generally Accepted System Security Principles (GSSP)
is an  outgrowth of the popular National Research Council document
"Computers at  Risk."  It is expected that GSSP will enable the security
profession to raise the median ability level of information security
professionals. GSSP will also provide a documented metric for
determination of "due care" and "prudent  care" in cases involving
claims of negligence. It is expected to replace  the  current  system,
where the fate of the  manager  or  security administrator depends
largely on the eloquence of the attorney and the past exposure  of the
judge.  One track session will present the motivation  for creating
GSSP, the candidate pervasive principles, and current status.

